Here's the approach:

### 1. Define theme resource dictionaries

Create one `ResourceDictionary` per theme (e.g., `LightTheme.xaml`, `DarkTheme.xaml`, `HighContrastTheme.xaml`):

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Use the same keys in every theme file so controls resolve correctly regardless of which dictionary is active.

### 2. Swap themes at runtime

Create a helper that replaces the theme dictionary in `App.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries`:

```csharp
public static class ThemeManager
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove old theme (always the last dictionary added by us)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d is IThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(theme);

        // Persist choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** Tag your theme dictionaries with a marker interface (`IThemeDictionary`) so you can find and replace them reliably.

### 3. Reference theme colours with `DynamicResource`

`DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) is required so values update when you swap the dictionary:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource Accent}" Text="Go" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 4. Apply the saved theme on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
    ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(saved);
}
```

### 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker"
        Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string theme)
        ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- One `ResourceDictionary` per theme, identical keys across all three.
- Always use `DynamicResource` so swaps take effect immediately.
- Swap by removing/adding dictionaries in `MergedDictionaries`.
- Persist the choice with `Preferences` and restore it in `App()`.
